                        <p>
                            I was a full-time in-house consultant at Ericsson, one of the best know international Swedish brands (I even had a Sony Ericsson mobile one year prior).
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            It meant a decent salary jump but did not include paid time off, and the contract would end if the assignment concluded. I was employed by <b>SPLIT Stockholm</b>, but there was another agency in the middle called <b>Screen Interaction</b> (now <b>Daresay</b>). After the two agencies cut, my salary was far from what Ericsson paid for my work.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            During my first assignment, I was found and poached by one of the main UX teams in the company. After learning that I was the only consultant on the team without paid time off, Didier (my manager at Ericsson) required that my consultant contract be adjusted accordingly.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            Due to our team's performance and a lot of evangelism on the value of design, Ericsson decided to switch from consultants to hiring only full-time designers. As I was under a non-compete clause, I needed to start thinking of my next job.
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            So to retain me until I finished my part on a mission-critical project (which led to the award-winning <a href="/work/ericsson.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Ericsson Design System</a>), I was offered a month's salary as an assignment completion bonus.
                        </p>
